{"cursor":"3235","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Yvonne Feyerick NÃ¨vejean' (1900 - 1987) was one of the leaders of an\norganisation that helped hide Jewish children in Nazi-occupied Belgium during\nWorld War II. She was instrumental in hiding about 4000 children, http://www1.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/Microsoft%20Word%20-\n%205956.pdf many with Catholic families and institutions. After the war\nshe was honoured inside and outside Belgium. In 1965, she was designated as\nRighteous Among the Nations by Yad Vashem, the Holocaust Remembrance Authority\nin Jerusalem, and in 1996 a stamp was issued in Belgium bearing her image.\n\nBorn on November 15, 1900, in Gentbrugge, NÃ¨vejean studied at the University of\nGhent (Gand) and then in the USA where she was awarded a Master of Arts in\nSocial and Political sciences at New York State University . After her return to\nBelgium in 1928, she started to work at the National Agency for Children (Oeuvre\nNationale de l'Enfance; ONE), an organization that operated a network of\nchildren's homes throughout Belgium. She subsequently rose to head this organis-\nation. http://www.philagodu.be/generalculturel/CELEBRITES/Nevejan.html\n\nThe Nazis began to deport Belgian Jews in the summer of 1942. At that time\nNÃ¨vejean was approached by the ComitÃ© de DÃ©fence des Juifs en Belgique,\nBelgium's main Jewish underground organization (founded in 1942 by ), and asked\nto rescue Jewish children separated from their parents. Acting essentially on\nher own, NÃ¨vejean agreed to have ONE place children with families and in\ninstitutions in order to protect them. Ultimately, she saved the lives of some\n4,000 Jewish children.\n\nThe Jewish underground financed NÃ¨vejean's extensive rescue operation, but when\ntheir funds were not sufficient, NÃ¨vejean found funding from banks and from the\nLondon based Belgian government in exile and the Joint (American Jewish Joint\nDistribution Committee). The Gestapo tried to stop Nevejean's 